a Protection Regulation):</strong> Complies with EU regulations to protect personal data and privacy.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> This document is a general guideline. It is recommended to consult with legal counsel to ensure that your Terms of Use are fully compliant with local and international laws applicable to your business.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Terms of use','','inherit','closed','closed','','123-revision-v1','','','2024-07-31 12:04:45','2024-07-31 12:04:45','',123,'http://granjacob.com/blog/?p=124',0,'revision','',0),(125,1,'2024-08-01 23:35:53','2024-08-01 23:35:53','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Main information about NEPTUNEQL</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','NEPTUNEQL Main Menu','','publish','closed','closed','','main','','','2024-08-02 02:56:25','2024-08-02 02:56:25','',2,'http://granjacob.com/blog/?page_id=125',0,'page','',0),(126,1,'2024-08-01 23:35:53','2024-08-01 23:35:53','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Main information about NEPTUNEQL</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','NEPTUNEQL','','inherit','closed','closed','','125-revision-v1','','','2024-08-01 23:35:53','2024-08-01 23:35:53','',125,'http://granjacob.com/blog/?p=126',0,'revision','',0),(127,1,'2024-08-02 01:18:58','2024-08-02 01:18:58','','Gran Jacob Main Menu','','publish','closed','closed','','main','','','2024-08-02 01:22:49','2024-08-02 01:22:49','',82,'http://granjacob.com/blog/?page_id=127',0,'page','',0),(128,1,'2024-08-02 01:18:58','2024-08-02 01:18:58','','Gran Jacob Main Menu','','inherit','closed','closed','','127-revision-v1','','','2024-08-02 01:18:58','2024-08-02 01:18:58','',127,'http://granjacob.com/blog/?p=128',0,'revision','',0),(129,1,'2024-08-02 01:20:30','2024-08-02 01:20:30','','Gran Jacob Info Pages','','inherit','closed','closed','','121-revision-v1','','','2024-08-02 01:20:30','2024-08-02 01:20:30','',121,'http://granjacob.com/blog/?p=129',0,'revision','',0),(130,1,'2024-08-02 02:56:13','2024-08-02 02:56:13','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Main information about NEPTUNEQL</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','NEPTUNEQL Main Menu','','inherit','closed','closed','','125-revision-v1','','','2024-08-02 02:56:13','2024-08-02 02:56:13','',125,'http://granjacob.com/blog/?p=130',0,'revision','',0),(131,1,'2024-08-02 02:57:14','2024-08-02 02:57:14','<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":1} -->\n<h1 class=\"wp-block-heading\">NeptuneQL Documentation</h1>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Overview</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>NeptuneQL is a query language designed for defining database schemas and relationships between entities. It provides a simple syntax to create entities, relate them, and set default data with flexible wildcard capabilities.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Syntax Guide</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">1. Defining Entities</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To define an entity in NeptuneQL, use the following syntax:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<div class=\"bg-light p-3 border rounded overflow-auto\">\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><code>&lt;Entity name>( &lt;attributes list> );<br></code></pre>\n</div>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<div class=\"bg-light p-3 border rounded overflow-auto\">\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><code>Employee( id, name, phone );<br></code></pre>\n</div>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This creates an <code>Employee</code> entity with attributes <code>id</code>, <code>name</code>, and <code>phone</code>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">2. Creating Foreign Keys and Relationships</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To create a foreign key or establish a relationship between two entities, use the following syntax:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<div class=\"bg-light p-3 border rounded overflow-auto\">\n\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><code>&lt;Entity name>( &lt;attributeFrom> => &lt;Entity referenced>.&lt;attributeReferenced>, &lt;attributes list> );<br></code></pre>\n</div>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<div class=\"bg-light p-3 border rounded overflow-auto\">\n\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><code>Employee( id, name, phone, idSalary => Salary.id );<br>Salary( id, amount );<br></code></pre>\n</div>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In this example, the <code>Employee</code> entity has a foreign key <code>idSalary</code> that references the <code>id</code> attribute of the <code>Salary</code> entity.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">3. Using Wildcard Keywords</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>NeptuneQL allows you to set properties for columns of entities using wildcard keywords <code>anyEntity</code> and <code>anyAttribute</code>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">3.1 Using <code>anyEntity</code></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The <code>anyEntity</code> wildcard is used to reference any table.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Syntax:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<div class=\"bg-light p-3 border rounded overflow-auto\">\n\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><code>anyEntity.column.property = value;\n</code></pre>\n</div>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<div class=\"bg-light p-3 border rounded overflow-auto\">\n\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><code>anyEntity.id.type = int;<br>anyEntity.name.type = string;<br></code></pre>\n</div>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The above example sets the type of the <code>id</code> column to <code>int</code> and the type of the <code>name</code> column to <code>string</code> for all entities.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">3.2 Using <code>anyAttribute</code></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The <code>anyAttribute</code> wildcard can be used alone or combined with <code>anyEntity</code> to reference any attribute across all entities.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Syntax:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<div class=\"bg-light p-3 border rounded overflow-auto\">\n\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><code>anyAttribute.type = int;<br>anyEntity.anyAttribute.type = int;<br></code></pre>\n</div>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<div class=\"bg-light p-3 border rounded overflow-auto\">\n\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><code>anyAttribute.type = int;<br>Employee.anyAttribute.type = int;<br></code></pre>\n</div>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The first line sets the type for all attributes to <code>int</code>, while the second line sets the type for all attributes of the <code>Employee</code> entity to <code>int</code>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">4. Setting Default Data for an Entity</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To set default data for an entity, use the following syntax:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<div class=\"bg-light p-3 border rounded overflow-auto\">\n\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><code>&lt;Entity name>( &lt;attributes list> ) {<br>    ( &lt;values list 1> ), ... , (&lt;values list n>)<br>}<br></code></pre>\n</div>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<div class=\"bg-light p-3 border rounded overflow-auto\">\n\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><code>Salary( amount ) { 20000, 30000, 40000, 50000 }<br></code></pre>\n</div>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This sets default values for the <code>amount</code> attribute in the <code>Salary</code> entity.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Using Multiple Columns</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When you use multiple columns, you must group the values for each row using parentheses:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<div class=\"bg-light p-3 border rounded overflow-auto\">\n\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><code>Salary( id, amount ) { (\'1\', \'20000\'), (\'2\', \'30000\'), (\'3\', \'40000\'), (\'4\', \'50000\') }<br></code></pre>\n</div>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This example sets default values for both <code>id</code> and <code>amount</code> attributes in the <code>Salary</code> entity.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Summary</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Entities</strong>: Define with <code>&lt;Entity name&gt;( &lt;attributes list&gt; );</code></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Relationships</strong>: Define foreign keys with <code>&lt;Entity name&gt;( &lt;attributeFrom&gt; =&gt; &lt;Entity referenced&gt;.&lt;attributeReferenced&gt;, &lt;attributes list&gt; );</code></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Wildcards</strong>:<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><code>anyEntity</code></strong>: Use to set properties globally across all entities.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><code>anyAttribute</code></strong>: Use to set properties for all attributes across all or specific entities.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list --></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Default Data</strong>: Set with <code>&lt;Entity name&gt;( &lt;attributes list&gt; ) { ... }</code></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>NeptuneQL provides a simple yet powerful syntax for defining and managing database schemas and relationships with flexibility for both schema definition and default data management. Use the examples and syntax rules above to guide your use of NeptuneQL effectively.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Documentation','','publish','closed','closed','','documentation','','','2024-08-02 04:52:40','2024-08-02 04:52:40','',125,'http://granjacob.com/blog/?page_id=131',0,'page','',0),(132,1,'2024-08-02 02:57:07','2024-08-02 02:57:07','<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":1} -->\n<h1 class=\"wp-block-heading\">NeptuneQL Documentation</h1>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Overview</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>NeptuneQL is a query language designed for defining database schemas and relationships between entities. It provides a simple syntax to create entities, relate them, and set default data with flexible wildcard capabilities.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Syntax Guide</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">1. Defining Entities</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To define an entity in NeptuneQL, use the following syntax:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">plaintextCopiar código<code>&lt;Entity name&gt;( &lt;attributes list&gt; );\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">plaintextCopiar código<code>Employee( id, name, phone );\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This creates an <code>Employee</code> entity with attributes <code>id</code>, <code>name</code>, and <code>phone</code>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">2. Creating Foreign Keys and Relationships</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To create a foreign key or establish a relationship between two entities, use the following syntax:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">plaintextCopiar código<code>&lt;Entity name&gt;( &lt;attributeFrom&gt; =&gt; &lt;Entity referenced&gt;.&lt;attributeReferenced&gt;, &lt;attributes list&gt; );\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">plaintextCopiar código<code>Employee( id, name, phone, idSalary =&gt; Salary.id );\nSalary( id, amount );\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In this example, the <code>Employee</code> entity has a foreign key <code>idSalary</code> that references the <code>id</code> attribute of the <code>Salary</code> entity.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">3. Using Wildcard Keywords</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>NeptuneQL allows you to set properties for columns of entities using wildcard keywords <code>anyEntity</code> and <code>anyAttribute</code>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">3.1 Using <code>anyEntity</code></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The <code>anyEntity</code> wildcard is used to reference any table.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Syntax:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">plaintextCopiar código<code>anyEntity.column.property = value;\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">plaintextCopiar código<code>anyEntity.id.type = int;\nanyEntity.name.type = string;\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The above example sets the type of the <code>id</code> column to <code>int</code> and the type of the <code>name</code> column to <code>string</code> for all entities.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">3.2 Using <code>anyAttribute</code></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The <code>anyAttribute</code> wildcard can be used alone or combined with <code>anyEntity</code> to reference any attribute across all entities.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Syntax:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">plaintextCopiar código<code>anyAttribute.type = int;\nanyEntity.anyAttribute.type = int;\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">plaintextCopiar código<code>anyAttribute.type = int;\nEmployee.anyAttribute.type = int;\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The first line sets the type for all attributes to <code>int</code>, while the second line sets the type for all attributes of the <code>Employee</code> entity to <code>int</code>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">4. Setting Default Data for an Entity</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To set default data for an entity, use the following syntax:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">plaintextCopiar código<code>&lt;Entity name&gt;( &lt;attributes list&gt; ) {\n    ( &lt;values list 1&gt; ), ... , (&lt;values list n&gt;)\n}\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">plaintextCopiar código<code>Salary( amount ) { 20000, 30000, 40000, 50000 }\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This sets default values for the <code>amount</code> attribute in the <code>Salary</code> entity.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Using Multiple Columns</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When you use multiple columns, you must group the values for each row using parentheses:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">plaintextCopiar código<code>Salary( id, amount ) { (\'1\', \'20000\'), (\'2\', \'30000\'), (\'3\', \'40000\'), (\'4\', \'50000\') }\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This example sets default values for both <code>id</code> and <code>amount</code> attributes in the <code>Salary</code> entity.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Summary</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Entities</strong>: Define with <code>&lt;Entity name>( &lt;attributes list> );</code></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Relationships</strong>: Define foreign keys with <code>&lt;Entity name>( &lt;attributeFrom> => &lt;Entity referenced>.&lt;attributeReferenced>, &lt;attributes list> );</code></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Wildcards</strong>:<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><code>anyEntity</code></strong>: Use to set properties globally across all entities.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><code>anyAttribute</code></strong>: Use to set properties for all attributes across all or specific entities.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list --></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Default Data</strong>: Set with <code>&lt;Entity name>( &lt;attributes list> ) { ... }</code></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>NeptuneQL provides a simple yet powerful syntax for defining and managing database schemas and relationships with flexibility for both schema definition and default data management. Use the examples and syntax rules above to guide your use of NeptuneQL effectively.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Documentation','','inherit','closed','closed','','131-revision-v1','','','2024-08-02 02:57:07','2024-08-02 02:57:07','',131,'http://granjacob.com/blog/?p=132',0,'revision','',0),(133,1,'2024-08-02 02:59:39','2024-08-02 02:59:39','<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":1} -->\n<h1 class=\"wp-block-heading\">NeptuneQL Documentation</h1>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Overview</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>NeptuneQL is a que