item -->\n<li><strong>Entities</strong>: Define with <code>&lt;Entity name&gt;( &lt;attributes list&gt; );</code></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Relationships</strong>: Define foreign keys with <code>&lt;Entity name&gt;( &lt;attributeFrom&gt; =&gt; &lt;Entity referenced&gt;.&lt;attributeReferenced&gt;, &lt;attributes list&gt; );</code></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Wildcards</strong>:<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><code>anyEntity</code></strong>: Use to set properties globally across all entities.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><code>anyAttribute</code></strong>: Use to set properties for all attributes across all or specific entities.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list --></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Default Data</strong>: Set with <code>&lt;Entity name&gt;( &lt;attributes list&gt; ) { ... }</code></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>NeptuneQL provides a simple yet powerful syntax for defining and managing database schemas and relationships with flexibility for both schema definition and default data management. Use the examples and syntax rules above to guide your use of NeptuneQL effectively.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Documentation','','inherit','closed','closed','','131-revision-v1','','','2024-08-02 03:00:09','2024-08-02 03:00:09','',131,'http://granjacob.com/blog/?p=138',0,'revision','',0),(139,1,'2024-08-02 03:00:13','2024-08-02 03:00:13','<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":1} -->\n<h1 class=\"wp-block-heading\">NeptuneQL Documentation</h1>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Overview</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>NeptuneQL is a query language designed for defining database schemas and relationships between entities. It provides a simple syntax to create entities, relate them, and set default data with flexible wildcard capabilities.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Syntax Guide</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">1. Defining Entities</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To define an entity in NeptuneQL, use the following syntax:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><code>&lt;Entity name>( &lt;attributes list> );<br></code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><code>Employee( id, name, phone );<br></code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This creates an <code>Employee</code> entity with attributes <code>id</code>, <code>name</code>, and <code>phone</code>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">2. Creating Foreign Keys and Relationships</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To create a foreign key or establish a relationship between two entities, use the following syntax:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><code>&lt;Entity name>( &lt;attributeFrom> => &lt;Entity referenced>.&lt;attributeReferenced>, &lt;attributes list> );<br></code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><code>Employee( id, name, phone, idSalary => Salary.id );<br>Salary( id, amount );<br></code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In this example, the <code>Employee</code> entity has a foreign key <code>idSalary</code> that references the <code>id</code> attribute of the <code>Salary</code> entity.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">3. Using Wildcard Keywords</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>NeptuneQL allows you to set properties for columns of entities using wildcard keywords <code>anyEntity</code> and <code>anyAttribute</code>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">3.1 Using <code>anyEntity</code></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The <code>anyEntity</code> wildcard is used to reference any table.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Syntax:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">plaintextCopiar código<code>anyEntity.column.property = value;\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><code>anyEntity.id.type = int;<br>anyEntity.name.type = string;<br></code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The above example sets the type of the <code>id</code> column to <code>int</code> and the type of the <code>name</code> column to <code>string</code> for all entities.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">3.2 Using <code>anyAttribute</code></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The <code>anyAttribute</code> wildcard can be used alone or combined with <code>anyEntity</code> to reference any attribute across all entities.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Syntax:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><code>anyAttribute.type = int;<br>anyEntity.anyAttribute.type = int;<br></code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><code>anyAttribute.type = int;<br>Employee.anyAttribute.type = int;<br></code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The first line sets the type for all attributes to <code>int</code>, while the second line sets the type for all attributes of the <code>Employee</code> entity to <code>int</code>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">4. Setting Default Data for an Entity</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To set default data for an entity, use the following syntax:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><code>&lt;Entity name>( &lt;attributes list> ) {<br>    ( &lt;values list 1> ), ... , (&lt;values list n>)<br>}<br></code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><code>Salary( amount ) { 20000, 30000, 40000, 50000 }<br></code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This sets default values for the <code>amount</code> attribute in the <code>Salary</code> entity.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Using Multiple Columns</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When you use multiple columns, you must group the values for each row using parentheses:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><code>Salary( id, amount ) { (\'1\', \'20000\'), (\'2\', \'30000\'), (\'3\', \'40000\'), (\'4\', \'50000\') }<br></code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This example sets default values for both <code>id</code> and <code>amount</code> attributes in the <code>Salary</code> entity.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Summary</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Entities</strong>: Define with <code>&lt;Entity name&gt;( &lt;attributes list&gt; );</code></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Relationships</strong>: Define foreign keys with <code>&lt;Entity name&gt;( &lt;attributeFrom&gt; =&gt; &lt;Entity referenced&gt;.&lt;attributeReferenced&gt;, &lt;attributes list&gt; );</code></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Wildcards</strong>:<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><code>anyEntity</code></strong>: Use to set properties globally across all entities.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><code>anyAttribute</code></strong>: Use to set properties for all attributes across all or specific entities.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list --></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Default Data</strong>: Set with <code>&lt;Entity name&gt;( &lt;attributes list&gt; ) { ... }</code></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>NeptuneQL provides a simple yet powerful syntax for defining and managing database schemas and relationships with flexibility for both schema definition and default data management. Use the examples and syntax rules above to guide your use of NeptuneQL effectively.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Documentation','','inherit','closed','closed','','131-revision-v1','','','2024-08-02 03:00:13','2024-08-02 03:00:13','',131,'http://granjacob.com/blog/?p=139',0,'revision','',0),(140,1,'2024-08-02 04:13:22','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','Auto Draft','','auto-draft','closed','closed','','','','','2024-08-02 04:13:22','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'http://granjacob.com/blog/?page_id=140',0,'page','',0),(141,1,'2024-08-02 04:16:13','2024-08-02 04:16:13','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In today\'s rapidly evolving technological landscape, efficient and intuitive data management systems are crucial for handling complex data structures. As organizations grow and the volume of data increases exponentially, there arises a need for a robust query language that can cater to diverse data requirements. Enter NEPTUNEQL, a modern query language designed to facilitate seamless interaction with relational data models, providing both simplicity and power to developers and data analysts.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Background and Motivation</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>NEPTUNEQL was conceived with the vision of simplifying complex data interactions while maintaining the flexibility needed to support dynamic and evolving data schemas. Traditional query languages often present challenges when dealing with intricate data relationships and transformations, leading to cumbersome queries and potential performance bottlenecks. NEPTUNEQL aims to address these issues by offering a streamlined syntax and powerful abstraction capabilities.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The development of NEPTUNEQL is driven by the need to provide a more human-readable and developer-friendly language that bridges the gap between traditional SQL and modern data processing needs. Its design is inspired by the requirements of enterprises that deal with large-scale data and necessitate efficient querying mechanisms to extract valuable insights.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Design Principles</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The construction of NEPTUNEQL is guided by several core design principles:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Simplicity and Clarity</strong>: NEPTUNEQL syntax is crafted to be intuitive and easy to understand, reducing the learning curve for new users and enabling rapid adoption across teams. The language structure prioritizes clarity, allowing users to express complex queries in a concise manner.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Flexibility and Extensibility</strong>: Recognizing the diverse needs of different industries, NeptuneQL is built to be flexible and extensible. It supports various data types and operations, enabling users to define custom rules and transformations to meet specific business logic requirements.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Powerful Data Manipulation</strong>: NEPTUNEQL is designed to handle complex data relationships and provide advanced data manipulation capabilities. It allows users to define and traverse relationships between entities effortlessly, making it ideal for applications that require sophisticated data interactions.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Scalability and Performance</strong>: As a language built for modern data environments, NeptuneQL emphasizes scalability and performance optimization. Its architecture is optimized to handle large datasets efficiently, ensuring that queries execute quickly even as data volumes grow.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Language Construction</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The construction of NeptuneQL involves several key components:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Grammar Definition</strong>: NEPTUNEQL\'s grammar is defined using ANTLR, a powerful parser generator that allows the creation of a formal language specification. This grammar defines the syntax and structure of NEPTUNEQL, outlining how queries are parsed and interpreted.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Abstract Syntax Tree (AST)</strong>: Upon parsing a NEPTUNEQL query, an Abstract Syntax Tree (AST) is generated. The AST represents the hierarchical structure of the query, allowing for further analysis and transformation.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Visitor and Listener Patterns</strong>: NEPTUNEQL employs both visitor and listener patterns for traversing the AST. These patterns enable the execution of specific actions as different parts of the query are processed, facilitating tasks such as validation, optimization, and transformation.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Rule-Based Transformation</strong>: NEPTUNEQL supports rule-based transformations, allowing users to define custom rules that modify query behavior. This feature provides flexibility in adapting the language to meet specific application needs.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Use Cases</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>NEPTUNEQL is designed to cater to a wide range of use cases, including but not limited to:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Data Integration</strong>: Seamlessly integrating data from various sources and transforming it into a unified view for analysis.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Complex Queries</strong>: Constructing intricate queries involving multiple relationships and transformations with ease.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Custom Reporting</strong>: Generating customized reports that require specific data manipulations and aggregations.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Data Validation</strong>: Implementing data validation rules to ensure data integrity and consistency.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Conclusion</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>NEPTUNEQL represents a significant advancement in query language design, offering a modern, flexible, and powerful tool for managing complex data environments. By prioritizing simplicity, flexibility, and performance, NEPTUNEQL empowers users to harness the full potential of </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','NEPTUNEQL','','inherit','closed','closed','','2-autosave-v1','','','2024-08-02 04:16:13','2024-08-02 04:16:13','',2,'http://granjacob.com/blog/?p=141',0,'revision','',0),(143,1,'2024-08-02 04:44:56','2024-08-02 04:44:56','<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":1} -->\n<h1 class=\"wp-block-heading\">NeptuneQL Documentation</h1>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Overview</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>NeptuneQL is a query language designed for defining database schemas and relationships between entities. It provides a simple syntax to create entities, relate them, and set default data with flexible wildcard capabilities.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Syntax Guide</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">1. Defining Entities</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To define an entity in NeptuneQL, use the following syntax:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<div class=\"bg-light p-3 border rounded overflow-auto\">\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><code>&lt;Entity name>( &lt;attributes list> );<br></code></pre>\n</div>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><code>Employee( id, name, phone );<br></code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This creates an <code>Employee</code> entity with attributes <code>id</code>, <code>name</code>, and <code>phone</code>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">2. Creating Foreign Keys and Relationships</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To create a foreign key or establish a relationship between two entities, use the following syntax:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><code>&lt;Entity name>( &lt;attributeFrom> => &lt;Entity referenced>.&lt;attributeReferenced>, &lt;attributes list> );<br></code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><code>Employee( id, name, phone, idSalary => Salary.id );<br>Salary( id, amount );<br></code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In this example, the <code>Employee</code> entity has a foreign key <code>idSalary</code> that references the <code>id</code> attribute of the <code>Salary</code> entity.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">3. Using Wildcard Keywords</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>NeptuneQL allows you to set properties for columns of entities using wildcard keywords <code>anyEntity</code> and <code>anyAttribute</code>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">3.1 Using <code>anyEntity</code></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The <code>anyEntity</code> wildcard is used to reference any table.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Syntax:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">plaintextCopiar código<code>anyEntity.column.property = value;\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><code>anyEntity.id.type = int;<br>anyEntity.name.type = string;<br></code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The above example sets the type of the <code>id</code> column to <code>int</code> and the type of the <code>name</code> column to <code>string</code> for all entities.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">3.2 Using <code>anyAttribute</code></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The <code>anyAttribute</code> wildcard can be used alone or combined with <code>anyEntity</code> to reference any attribute across all entities.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Syntax:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><code>anyAttribute.type = int;<br>anyEntity.anyAttribute.type = int;<br></code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><code>anyAttribute.type = int;<br>Employee.anyAttribute.type = int;<br></code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The first line sets the type for all attributes to <code>int</code>, while the second line sets the type for all attributes of the <code>Employee</code> entity to <code>int</code>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">4. Setting Default Data for an Entity</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To set default data for an entity, use the following syntax:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><code>&lt;Entity name>( &lt;attributes list> ) {<br>    ( &lt;values list 1> ), ... , (&lt;values list n>)<br>}<br></code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><code>Salary( amount ) { 20000, 30000, 40000, 50000 }<br></code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This sets default values for the <code>amount</code> attribute in the <code>Salary</code> entity.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Using Multiple Columns</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When you use multiple columns, you must group the values for each row using parentheses:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><code>Salary( id, amount ) { (\'1\', \'20000\'), (\'2\', \'30000\'), (\'3\', \'40000\'), (\'4\', \'50000\') }<br></code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This example sets default values for both <code>id</code> and <code>amount</code> attributes in the <code>Salary</code> entity.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Summary</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Entities</strong>: Define with <code>&lt;Entity name&gt;( &lt;attributes list&gt; );</code></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Relationships</strong>: Define foreign keys with <code>&lt;Entity name&gt;( &lt;attributeFrom&gt; =&gt; &lt;Entity referenced&gt;.&lt;attributeReferenced&gt;, &lt;attributes list&gt; );</code></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Wildcards</strong>:<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><code>anyEntity</code></strong>: Use to set properties globally across all entities.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><code>anyAttribute</code></strong>: Use to set properties for all attributes across all or specific entities.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list --></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Default Data</strong>: Set with <code>&lt;Entity name&gt;( &lt;attributes list&gt; ) { ... }</code></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>NeptuneQL provides a simple yet powerful syntax for defining and managing database schemas and relationships with flexibility for both schema definition and default data management. Use the examples and syntax rules above to guide your use of NeptuneQL effectively.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Documentation','','inherit','closed','closed','','131-revision-v1','','','2024-08-02 04:44:56','2024-08-02 04:44:56','',131,'http://granjacob.com/blog/?p=143',0,'revision','',0),(144,1,'2024-08-02 04:45:53','2024-08-02 04:45:53','<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":1} -->\n<h1 class=\"wp-block-heading\">NeptuneQL Documentation</h1>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Overview</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>NeptuneQL is a query language designed for defining database schemas and relationships between entities. It provides a simple syntax to create entities, relate them, and set default data with flexible wildcard capabilities.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Syntax Guide</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">1. Defining Entities</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To define an entity in NeptuneQL, use the following syntax:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<div class=\"bg-light p-3 border rounded overflow-auto\">\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><code>&lt;Entity name>( &lt;attributes list> );<br></code></pre>\n</div>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<div class=\"bg-light p-3 border rounded overflow-auto\">\n\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><code>Employee( id, name, phone );<br></code></pre>\n</div>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This creates an <code>Employee</code> entity with attributes <code>id</code>, <code>name</code>, and <code>phone</code>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">2. Creating Foreign Keys and Relationships</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To create a foreign key or establish a relationship between two entities, use the following syntax:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><code>&lt;Entity name>( &lt;attributeFrom> => &lt;Entity referenced>.&lt;attributeReferenced>, &lt;attributes list> );<br></code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><code>Employee( id, name, phone, idSalary => Salary.id );<br>Salary( id, amount );<br></code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In this example, the <code>Employee</code> entity has a foreign key <code>idSalary</code> that references the <code>id</code> attribute of the <code>Salary</code> entity.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">3. Using Wildcard Keywords</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>NeptuneQL allows you to set properties for columns of entities using wildcard keywords <code>anyEntity</code> and <code>anyAttribute</code>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">3.1 Using <code>anyEntity</code></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The <code>anyEntity</code> wildcard is used to reference any table.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Syntax:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">plaintextCopiar código<code>anyEntity.column.property = value;\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><code>anyEntity.id.type = int;<br>anyEntity.name.type = string;<br></code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The above example sets the type of the <code>id</code> column to <code>int</code> and the type of the <code>name</code> column to <code>string</code> for all entities.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">3.2 Using <code>anyAttribute</code></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The <code>anyAttribute</code> wildcard can be used alone or combined with <code>anyEntity</code> to reference any attribute across all entities.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Syntax:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><code>anyAttribute.type = int;<br>anyEntity.anyAttribute.type = int;<br></code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><code>anyAttribute.type = int;<br>Employee.anyAttribute.type = int;<br></code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The first line sets the type for all attributes to <code>int</code>, while the second line sets the type for all attributes of the <code>Employee</code> entity to <code>int</code>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">4. Setting Default Data for an Entity</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To set default data for an entity, use the following syntax:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><code>&lt;Entity name>( &lt;attributes list> ) {<br>    ( &lt;values list 1> ), ... , (&lt;values list n>)<br>}<br></code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><code>Salary( amount ) { 20000, 30000, 40000, 50000 }<br></code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This sets default values for the <code>amount</code> attribute in the <code>Salary</code> entity.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Using Multiple Columns</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When you use multiple columns, you must group the values for each row using parentheses:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><code>Salary( id, amount ) { (\'1\', \'20000\'), (\'2\', \'30000\'), (\'3\', \'40000\'), (\'4\', \'50000\') }<br></code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This example sets default values for both <code>id</code> and <code>amount</code> attributes in the <code>Salary</code> entity.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Summary</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Entities</strong>: Define with <code>&lt;Entity name&gt;( &lt;attributes list&gt; );</code></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Relationships</strong>: Define foreign keys with <code>&lt;Entity name&gt;( &lt;attributeFrom&gt; =&gt; &lt;Entity referenced&gt;.&lt;attributeReferenced&gt;, &lt;attributes list&gt; );</code></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Wildcards</strong>:<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><code>anyEntity</code></strong>: Use to set properties globally across all entities.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><code>anyAttribute</code></strong>: Use to set properties for all attributes across all or specific entities.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list --></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Default Data</strong>: Set with <code>&lt;Entity name&gt;( &lt;attributes list&gt; ) { ... }</code></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>NeptuneQL provides a simple yet powerful syntax for defining and managing database schemas and relationships with flexibility for both schema definition and default data management. Use the examples and syntax rules above to guide your use of NeptuneQL effectively.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Documentation','','inherit','closed','closed','','131-revision-v1','','','2024-08-02 04:45:53','2024-08-02 04:45:53','',131,'http://granjacob.com/blog/?p=144',0,'revision','',0),(145,1,'2024-08-02 04:51:31','2024-08-02 04:51:31','<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":1} -->\n<h1 class=\"wp-block-heading\">NeptuneQL Documentation</h1>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Overview</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>NeptuneQL is a query language designed for defining database schemas and relationships between entities. It provides a simple syntax to create entities, relate them, and set default data wi